CNCP v1 25314
{
  "concept": "vuejs/core#12012: Generic slot props in loops with discriminated union props definition breaks slot prop type",
  "version": "1.0",
  "created_at": "2026-03-15T04:22:10.145446+00:00",
  "text": "Generic slot props in loops with discriminated union props definition breaks slot prop type\n\n### Vue version\r\n\r\n^5.0\r\n\r\n### Link to minimal reproduction\r\n\r\nhttps://play.vuejs.org/#\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. In a component, define a generic type, and use it as the array type for a prop.\r\nE.g.\r\n```vue\r\n<script\r\n  setup\r\n  lang=\"ts\"\r\n  generic=\"T extends { id: number }\"\r\n>\r\ndefineProps<{\r\n  items: T[],\r\n}>()\r\n</script>\r\n```\r\n\r\n2. Define a default slot, with the generic as a slot prop.\r\nE.g.\r\n```ts\r\ndefineSlots<{\r\n  default (props: {\r\n    item: T,\r\n  }): any\r\n}>()\r\n```\r\n\r\n3. In a component use `defineSlots` to define props with a discriminated union.\r\nE.g.\r\n```ts\r\ndefineProps<(\r\n  | { someProp: false }\r\n  | { someProp: true }\r\n)>()\r\n```\r\n\r\n4. Declare a variable that fits the prop of the first component, with an additional property.\r\nE.g.\r\n```ts\r\nconst items = [{\r\n  id: 1,\r\n  somePropertyNotInThePropDefinition: 'foo'\r\n}]\r\n```\r\n\r\n5. Use the first component in the template, with the variable as the prop, and use the `v-slot` directive so that the slot prop is available. Inside the slot body, access the additional property.\r\nE.g.\r\n```vue\r\n<ComponentWithGenericSlot\r\n  :items=\"items\"\r\n  v-slot=\"{ item }\"\r\n>\r\n  {{ item.somePropertyNotInThePropDefinition }}\r\n</ComponentWithGenericSlot>\r\n```\r\n\r\n### What is expected?\r\n\r\nThe additional property should be typed correctly with the additional property in the slot prop.\r\n\r\n### What is actually happening?\r\n\r\nThe additional property is not recognized. The type of the slot prop is the type of the generic, and nothing else.\r\n\r\n### System Info\r\n\r\n```shell\r\nSystem:\r\n    OS: macOS 15.0\r\n    CPU: (8) arm64 Apple M1\r\n    Memory: 50.31 MB / 16.00 GB\r\n    Shell: 5.9 - /bin/zsh\r\n  Binaries:\r\n    Node: 20.17.0 - /usr/local/bin/node\r\n    Yarn: 1.22.19 - /opt/homebrew/bin/yarn\r\n    npm: 10.8.2 - /usr/local/bin/npm\r\n    pnpm: 7.33.7 - /opt/homebrew/bin/pnpm\r\n    bun: 1.0.14 - /opt/homebrew/bin/bun\r\n  Browsers:\r\n    Safari: 18.0\r\n  npmPackages:\r\n    vue: ^3.5.0 => 3.5.8\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n### Any additional comments?\r\n\r\nThis started with Vue 5.5. Changing the typescript or vue-tsc versions doesn't affect this.\r\n\r\nCuriously, in my local project, when using vue-tsc, wrapping the `defineProp` in an empty `withDefaults` was required to produce the described behaviour. This is not the case in the play.vuejs.org editor.",
  "language": "en",
  "keywords": [
    "scope: types"
  ],
